Rating: 4
OMG!! This was so incredible!! I used dried and rehydrated porcinis. I soaked them for 30 minutes and patted them very dry using multiple paper towels, then chopped them coarsely and put them on a premade cornmeal crust from Vicolo which is made in the San Francisco area, which I had previously drizzled with Napa Valley Oil Company EVOO (a true find and staple in my kitchen). I added a little freshly ground black pepper and sea salt and then baked in the middle of a preheated oven at 475 on a cookie sheet for about 20 minutes until the taleggio and crust were golden brown. No truffle oil was available in my larder but really not necessary with the intense flavor of the porcinis melding perfectly with the equally large flavor of the telaggio. Will make it again later this weekend for my boyfriend. He will devour it!!

Rating: 4
I think this is my favorite pizza recipe ever (second to the Three-Cheese Pizza with Pancetta and Mushrooms, on this site). I followed other reviewers' advice and sauteed the mushrooms first in oil, then set the oven temp to 450 rather than 500. I also oiled the parchment paper after one reviewer complained that the pizza stuck to it. The parchment burned horribly, but the pizza lifted off like a dream, and was a little burn-y on the bottom, which made it even more delicious. I can't wait to make this again!

